🔹 1. @Data (Lombok)
@Data

👉 Use:

Automatically generates:
getters
setters
toString()
equals() & hashCode()

👉 Without this → you must write all methods manually.

⚠️ Note: You already wrote setters & toString → so @Data is partly unnecessary here.

🔹 2. @Entity
@Entity

👉 Use:

Marks this class as a JPA Entity (Database Table)

👉 Meaning:

Hibernate will treat this class as a table in DB.

➡️ Without this → class is just a normal Java class ❌

🔹 3. @Table(name="product")
@Table(name="product")

👉 Use:

Specifies table name in database

👉 If you don’t use it:

Table name = class name → Product

👉 Here:

Table name will be → product
🔹 4. @Id
@Id
private long pid;

👉 Use:

Marks this field as Primary Key

👉 Why important?

Every table must have a unique identifier

➡️ Without @Id → Hibernate throws error ❌

🔹 Fields (No Annotation)
private String pname;
private double pprice;

👉 These become columns automatically in DB.

👉 Column names:

pname
pprice
🔥 Summary (Very Important)
Annotation	Purpose
@Entity	Makes class → DB table
@Table	Custom table name
@Id	Primary key
@Data	Auto generate methods
⚡ Why Annotations Are Powerful

Without annotations ❌:

You need XML configuration
More boilerplate code
Hard to maintain

With annotations ✅:

Clean code
Less coding
Easy to understand
Faster development
🚀 Real-Life Analogy

Think of annotations like labels on a box 📦

@Entity → "This is a database table"
@Id → "This is unique ID"
@Table → "Use this name in DB"
⚠️ Important Suggestion (Best Practice)

Since you're using Lombok:

👉 Remove manual setters & toString OR remove @Data

Better version:

@Data
@Entity
@Table(name="product")
public class Product {

    @Id
    private long pid;

    private String pname;
    private double pprice;
}